Come for the Optimism, stay for the in-depth analyses of tech companies and=
 trends:
Hi friends =F0=9F=91=8B,
Happy Friday and welcome to our 17th Weekly Dose of Optimism.=20
The Weekly Dose is brought to you by=E2=80=A6Masterworks [ https://substack=
=2Ecom/redirect/14581005-d26b-486e-a273-196c70241f84?r=3D9p0gt ]
Beeeeeep! What=E2=80=99s that sound? It=E2=80=99s your portfolio flatlining=
 from an imploding stock market, crypto meltdown, and the worst inflation s=
ince Saturday Night Fever. How can you shock it back to life? (Note: This h=
as nothing to do with bell bottoms.)
Try an asset that the ultra-wealthy have used to boost their gains for cent=
uries: blue-chip art, which has outpaced the S&P by a whopping 131% over th=
e last 26 years. But now, you don=E2=80=99t need to be a Studio 54 VIP to i=
nvest in Picassos and Basquiats. You just need Masterworks.
With this award-winning platform, anyone can invest in shares of multi-mill=
ion dollar art, for just a fraction of the price of the entire work. (Even =
Packy, who may one day fulfill his dream of investing in a Banksy.)=C2=A0
Their results are creating some seriously good vibes. Masterworks=E2=80=99 =
last sale realized a 33% net return for investors. (Cue: =E2=80=9CStayin=E2=
=80=99 Alive.=E2=80=9D)
Not Boring readers can skip their waitlist with this exclusive referral lin=
k. [ https://substack.com/redirect/953008c5-cc37-4822-b1a5-125787b2a407?r=
=3D9p0gt ]
See important Reg A disclosures. [ https://substack.com/redirect/d4e08f59-2=
fd9-41df-ab64-d0ba19324de4?r=3D9p0gt ]
(1) Vaccines to treat cancer possible by 2030, say BioNTech founders [ http=
s://substack.com/redirect/4cc7837e-bb5b-4aed-90ea-1401a6f7d9f1?r=3D9p0gt ]
Ian Sample [ https://substack.com/redirect/f8b9b916-df3e-4768-a1af-5e2437fb=
0533?r=3D9p0gt ] for The Guardian
It=E2=80=99s not everyday at Not Boring that we=E2=80=99re giving a positiv=
e shoutout to The Prof, but props where props are due: he brought this incr=
edible story to our attention. The company that partnered with Pfizer to ma=
nufacture its mRNA Covid vaccine is now claiming that similar technologies =
can be used to create cancer vaccines by the end of this decade. BioNTech, =
founded by a Husband-Wife duo profiled in this 2020 NYT=E2=80=99s piece [ h=
ttps://substack.com/redirect/aed8ba6b-6eac-472d-9087-bf1201c1a9c0?r=3D9p0gt=
 ], had been researching mRNA cancer vaccines prior to Covid, but when the =
emergency need for a vaccine occured, they pivoted. Now, flush with cash fr=
om the successful Pfizer Covid vaccine, the company has several cancer vacc=
ines already in clinical trials.
(2) These Tiny Ultra-Porous Crystals Could Transform Cancer Treatments and =
More [ https://substack.com/redirect/ac474898-7772-41ca-9a92-07912e043d8d?r=
=3D9p0gt ]
Dominique Mosbergen [ https://substack.com/redirect/ca2c6c03-cd9e-4ac8-bcd9=
-1d2d7ce25670?r=3D9p0gt ] for The Wall Street Journal
Imagine a tiny sponge that weighs as much as a couple of sugar cubes, but t=
hat contains so many itty bitty pores [ https://substack.com/redirect/d2e4a=
5e0-3989-4c74-945d-acf7d5ada874?r=3D9p0gt ] that its surface area equals th=
at of a football field. What if scientists could engineer the sponge to ser=
ve a variety of therapeutic purposes, including storing drugs and enhancing=
 cancer therapies?=C2=A0Such sponges exist, in a class of ultra-porous crys=
tals known as metal-organic frameworks, or MOFs.
Cancer is getting it from all sides this week. Good. Fuck cancer.=20
New research on sponge-like crystals known as metal-organic frameworks (MOF=
s) suggests that the crystalline compounds could transform cancer therapeut=
ics in various ways, from absorbing radiation that harms normal cells durin=
g radiation therapy to delivering drugs directly into cancer cells.
But MOFs aren=E2=80=99t cancer-specific. They might have applications in a =
number of important areas, from healthcare to energy and beyond. Chemists w=
ho the WSJ interviewed said =E2=80=9CMOFs could become as widespread as pol=
ymers, compounds that form the basis of many man-made materials like plasti=
cs, in the next decade or two.=E2=80=9D=20
Our ears perked up when we read that (or, our eyes perked up?). After readi=
ng Tsung Xu [ https://substack.com/redirect/e6f8caa4-2bbe-43e4-8a50-f00b408=
7fa8c?r=3D9p0gt ]=E2=80=99s excellent two [ https://substack.com/redirect/f=
3782e80-2420-49e3-8c4e-d5907e35bab2?r=3D9p0gt ]-parter [ https://substack.c=
om/redirect/d3c3a2be-6d1c-48c3-9714-0ed8604d9d87?r=3D9p0gt ] on materials i=
nnovation, in which he writes that synthetic polymers were the last real ma=
terials breakthrough at scale and argues that a new energy paradigm will co=
me with new materials, we=E2=80=99ve been on the lookout. MOFs, which can p=
ack 7,000 square meters of space into a single gram, seem incredibly cool (=
but beyond our comprehension. Howwww?).=20
Proponents believe that MOFs might also play a role in toxic gas detection,=
 tissue regeneration, and carbon capture. MOFs are expensive, but as costs =
come down, we=E2=80=99re excited to see the new applications that smart peo=
ple dream up with new materials.
(3) STARLINK AVIATION [ https://substack.com/redirect/740e1f08-4267-4b05-b1=
04-6163ad863dba?r=3D9p0gt ]
Wifi on airplanes is simultaneously absolutely mind-blowing and incredibly =
frustrating. On one hand, the fact that we can get wifi aboard a metal bird=
 flying 500 mph 36,000 feet in the air seems like one of the great technolo=
gical feats of our lifetime. On the other, now that we=E2=80=99ve been spoi=
led with superfast and capable wifi down on earth, the slow, glitchy and li=
mited airplane connection is one of modern human=E2=80=99s biggest annoyanc=
es. You know the bit:
You know what (or rather, who) else is absolutely mind-blowing and incredib=
ly frustrating? Elon Musk. Starlink, a spin-off product from Musk=E2=80=99s=
 second biggest company, has already made waves for bringing high-speed int=
ernet access to hard to reach places, such as the Ukraine. Now, with this a=
nnouncement, it=E2=80=99s bringing that same internet to aviation. At ~$200=
K per year with a 1-time installation fee of $150K, it seems like a no-brai=
ner for private jets that are often ferrying folks with hourly-rates higher=
 than the annual subscription fee. Hopefully, Starlink also strikes deals w=
ith commercial airliners, so we normal folk can get our grubby hands on som=
e of that sweet, sweet high-speed internet too!
(4) NASA=E2=80=99s Webb Takes Star-Filled Portrait of Pillars of Creation [=
 https://substack.com/redirect/468309db-11de-4eb3-84b4-b5de9449f03f?r=3D9p0=
gt ]
From NASA
NASA=E2=80=99s James Webb Space Telescope has captured a lush, highly detai=
led landscape =E2=80=93 the iconic Pillars of Creation =E2=80=93 where new =
stars are forming within dense clouds of gas and dust. The three-dimensiona=
l pillars look like majestic rock formations, but are far more permeable. T=
hese columns are made up of cool interstellar gas and dust that appear =E2=
=80=93 at times =E2=80=93 semi-transparent in near-infrared light.
Not going to be able to sleep tonight. Anytime one of these beautiful, surr=
eal images of the universe are published, I am left contemplating how I can=
 at once feel so infinitesimally small and also so singularly important. Th=
e =E2=80=9CPillars of Creation=E2=80=9D have been making people feel this w=
ay since 1995, when the Hubble Telescope first captured photos of the star-=
forming region. The Webb Telescope=E2=80=99s latest photo =E2=80=94 a near-=
infrared-light shot =E2=80=94 lets us peer deeper into the region and revea=
ls new stars being formed. Supposedly, the new imagery will allow researche=
rs to have a much deeper understanding of the region=E2=80=A6but for our pu=
rposes, we just think it=E2=80=99s beautiful.
(5) The race to Q>1 [ https://substack.com/redirect/18491cb9-ab20-4dad-b172=
-f62921268277?r=3D9p0gt ]
Chris Sacca [ https://substack.com/redirect/daca17e5-edee-4d59-b64c-7386125=
81c1e?r=3D9p0gt ] for Lowercarbon Capital
Q>1 is the Kitty Hawk moment for energy. It=E2=80=99s Lindbergh crossing th=
e Atlantic, Armstrong and Aldrin bouncing around the moon, and Bell calling=
 up Watson because it would be another 120 years before he could just text =
him memes.
Chris Sacca is famous for running (perhaps) the best returning VC fund of a=
ll-time: Lowercase Capital Fund 1 made early bets on Uber, Instagram, Twitt=
er and reportedly returned 250x to LPs. If you invested $100K in that fund,=
 it returned you $25M. After a two year stint on Shark Tank and a four year=
 retirement from investing, Sacca burst back on the scene with Lowercarbon =
Capital =E2=80=94 a climate-focused VC firm with the mission to unf*ck the =
planet.
Lowercarbon has been one of the most active climate investors of the past f=
ew years and on Wednesday it announced a $250M fund, Q>1, dedicated entirel=
y towards advancing fusion technologies. At Not Boring, we=E2=80=99ve writt=
en extensively on the Abundance Agenda, which in part advocates for the pro=
duction of a massive clean energy surplus from sources like nuclear, solar,=
 hydrogen, and new battery technologies. But we haven=E2=80=99t really cove=
red fusion, which seems like a miss. Fusion is the holy grail. If we can pu=
ll off fusion, we=E2=80=99ll have unlimited, cheap, clean energy to power a=
 whole new wave of innovations.
So what is Lowercase=E2=80=99s Q1 fund trying to achieve? It=E2=80=99s in t=
he name. Q>1 =E2=80=94 =E2=80=9Cthe relationship between the energy require=
d to ignite a fusion reaction and the energy the reaction itself produces i=
s known as the =E2=80=9Cfusion energy gain factor,=E2=80=9D and it is denot=
ed by the character Q.=E2=80=9D Q>1 is backing companies and technologies t=
hat will make the energy produced by fusion greater than the energy require=
d to ignite a fusion reaction.
If the Q>1 fund is successful, we might have a new best performing venture =
fund of all time.
